BOOK III

ODE I

ΤΗΕ first six Odes of this Book are remarkable for their sustained dignity of style and general unity of subject. They are all in the Alcaic metre and of considerable length, and all· deal with subJects of public and political interest. It is probable that their composition was at any rate suggested by Augustus, whose object it was to appeal in support of his politica] system not merely to the interests but to the feelings of his subJects (see Merivale, c. 41). Lines 1-4 of Ode I are a stately exordium to the whole six Odes rather than a particular introduction to the first ; indeed, as the introduction to a single Ode they would be exaggerated and unnatural.
